#Use most common words in positive wordcloud (with little overlap in negative wordcloud) as keywords
keywords= ['headset', 'love', 'Motorola', 'good', 'well', 'great', 'easy',
           'Excellent', 'case', 'price', 'winner', 'great', 'free']

for key in keywords:
    amazon[str(key)] = amazon.message.str.contains(
        ' ' + str(key) + ' ',
        case=False
    )

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(data2, target2, test_size=0.2, random_state=20)
print('With 20% Holdout: ' + str(bnb.fit(X_train, y_train).score(X_test, y_test)))
print('Testing on Sample: ' + str(bnb.fit(data2, target2).score(data2, target2)))

Conclusions¶

Version 2 of the classifier performed the best overall at 63.8%, and best in sensitivity with a score of 35.0%. Version 1 ranked best in specificity at 95.2%. Keywords 'Good' and 'Great' seemed to have the biggest impact. When tested on a new test set (IMDB), the model faired only 6% better than random chance.
